{'input': 'Can I get out of an arbitration agreement if the bank was late making a motion to compel?', 'output': "Now list several legal questions, with some basic case background where this information may be favorable to a consumer's case or legal writing requests that would be addressed by this writing. Make half of them examples that a lawyer may write as a prompt to an AI assistant, and the other half, examples that a consumer may write. Try to keep them under 700 BPE tokens in length:   ### Summary of the Case\n\n**Court and Case References:**\n- **Court:** United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit\n- **Case Numbers:** 16-16820, 16-16823\n- **Key Citations:** \n  - AT&T Mobility LLC v. Concepcion, 563 U.S. 333\n  - Garcia v. Wachovia Corp., 699 F.3d 1273\n  - S & H Contractors, Inc. v. A.J. Taft Coal Co., Inc., 906 F.2d 1507\nThis opinion cites:\n\n    At&T Mobility LLC v. Concepcion, 563 U.S. 333 (4 times)\n    S & H Contractors, Inc., a Corporation v. A.J. Taft … (2 times)\n    Fed. Sec. L. Rep. P 93,048 Mary Benoay, Cross-Appellant v. … (1 time)\n    Fed. Sec. L. Rep. P 95,761 Cyril Stone v. E.F. … (1 time)\n    In Re Checking Account Overdraft Litigation, 694 F. Supp. 2d … (1 time)\n\n**Background:**\nFive class actions were filed against Wells Fargo Bank by customers alleging unlawful overdraft fees. These actions were consolidated in 2009. The core issue arose when Wells Fargo sought to compel arbitration for unnamed class members after the District Court denied its earlier motion based on a claimed waiver of arbitration rights.\n\n**Key Points of the Appeal:**\n1. **Waiver of Arbitration Rights:** The District Court found Wells Fargo waived its rights by not timely moving to compel arbitration against unnamed plaintiffs. The appellate court determined this finding was erroneous.\n   \n2. **Contractual Agreements:** Plaintiffs had entered into customer agreements with Wells Fargo that mandated individual arbitration for disputes, explicitly prohibiting class-wide arbitration.\n\n3. **Timing of Motions:** \n   - Wells Fargo did not move to compel arbitration for named plaintiffs and instead filed an omnibus motion to dismiss.\n   - After the Supreme Court decision in *Concepcion*, Wells Fargo attempted to compel arbitration, but the District Court ruled it had waived its rights due to prior litigation activities.\n\n4. **Legal Precedents:** \n   - The appellate court referenced past rulings that emphasize the importance of timely notice regarding arbitration rights.\n   - The court distinguished between actions taken against named versus unnamed plaintiffs, concluding that Wells Fargo had preserved its right to arbitrate against unnamed plaintiffs.\n\n5. **Court's Jurisdiction:** The District Court lacked jurisdiction to compel arbitration for unnamed class members before class certification, complicating Wells Fargo’s ability to act.\n\n6. **Outcome:** The appellate court vacated the District Court’s ruling and remanded the case, concluding that Wells Fargo did not act inconsistently with its arbitration rights and, thus, did not waive those rights.\n\n### Conclusion\nThe Eleventh Circuit determined that Wells Fargo preserved its arbitration rights regarding unnamed class members and that the District Court’s ruling of waiver was unfounded. The case was remanded for further proceedings consistent with this opinion."},
